Importing libraries¶

In [1]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import re
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')

Data Extraction:¶

  • The core of the project involves scraping data from the following multiple pages of URLs from ebay website, which contain ipad and tablets of various brands
  • https://www.ebay.com/b/Tablets-eReaders/171485/bn_320042
  • The process for each category is as follows:
  • Making a request: The requests.get() function is used to fetch the HTML content of the specified URL. A successful request returns a Response [200], indicating a successful connection.
  • Parsing the HTML: BeautifulSoup is then used to parse the raw HTML text, making it easy to search for specific elements.
  • Finding data: CSS selectors like class_= <class="textual-display bsig__title__text"> and the tag is h3
In [3]:
url="https://www.ebay.com/b/Tablets-eReaders/171485/bn_320042"
res=requests.get(url)
res
Out[3]:
<Response [200]>
In [4]:
soup=BeautifulSoup(res.text, "html.parser")
print(soup)

import re
import pandas as pd

pattern = re.compile(
    r"""^(?P<name>[A-Za-z0-9\s\-\|\.]+)             # Laptop brand + model name
        (?=.*?(?P<screen>\d{1,2}\.?\d{0,1})[" ]?)   # Screen size (e.g. 14.1, 15.6)
        (?=.*?(?P<processor>(Celeron|Pentium|i3|i5|i7|i9|Ryzen\s?\d|AMD\s?\w+|Intel\s?\w+)[^,]*))?
        (?=.*?(?P<ram>\d{1,2}\s?GB))                # RAM size
        (?=.*?(?P<storage>\d{2,4}\s?GB\s?(SSD|HDD|eMMC|NVME)?)) # Storage
    """,
    re.IGNORECASE | re.VERBOSE
)

results = []
for line in text.split("\n"):
    m = pattern.search(line)
    if m:
        row = m.groupdict()
        row["raw_text"] = line
        results.append(row)

df1=pd.DataFrame(results)
df1

  • This regEX pattern is used for all the multiple pages to scrape.

results = []

import re
import pandas as pd

pattern = re.compile(
    r"""^(?P<name>[A-Za-z0-9\s\-\|\.]+)             # Laptop brand + model name
        (?=.*?(?P<screen>\d{1,2}\.?\d{0,1})[" ]?)   # Screen size (e.g. 14.1, 15.6)
        (?=.*?(?P<processor>(Celeron|Pentium|i3|i5|i7|i9|Ryzen\s?\d|AMD\s?\w+|Intel\s?\w+)[^,]*))?
        (?=.*?(?P<ram>\d{1,2}\s?GB))                # RAM size
        (?=.*?(?P<storage>\d{2,4}\s?GB\s?(SSD|HDD|eMMC|NVME)?)) # Storage
    """,
    re.IGNORECASE | re.VERBOSE
)

import re
import pandas as pd

pattern = re.compile(
    r"""^(?P<name>[A-Za-z0-9\s\-\|\.]+)             # Laptop brand + model name
        (?=.*?(?P<screen>\d{1,2}\.?\d{0,1})[" ]?)   # Screen size (e.g. 14.1, 15.6)
        (?=.*?(?P<processor>(Celeron|Pentium|i3|i5|i7|i9|Ryzen\s?\d|AMD\s?\w+|Intel\s?\w+)[^,]*))?
        (?=.*?(?P<ram>\d{1,2}\s?GB))                # RAM size
        (?=.*?(?P<storage>\d{2,4}\s?GB\s?(SSD|HDD|eMMC|NVME)?)) # Storage
    """,
    re.IGNORECASE | re.VERBOSE
)

import re
import pandas as pd

pattern = re.compile(
    r"""^(?P<name>[A-Za-z0-9\s\-\|\.]+)             # Laptop brand + model name
        (?=.*?(?P<screen>\d{1,2}\.?\d{0,1})[" ]?)   # Screen size (e.g. 14.1, 15.6)
        (?=.*?(?P<processor>(Celeron|Pentium|i3|i5|i7|i9|Ryzen\s?\d|AMD\s?\w+|Intel\s?\w+)[^,]*))?
        (?=.*?(?P<ram>\d{1,2}\s?GB))                # RAM size
        (?=.*?(?P<storage>\d{2,4}\s?GB\s?(SSD|HDD|eMMC|NVME)?)) # Storage
    """,
    re.IGNORECASE | re.VERBOSE
)

        results.append(row)

Detecting Outliers:¶

The IQR (Interquartile Range) method was used to detect outliers in all numerical columns as part of the non-visual analysis.

Steps:¶

  • Calculate Q1 (25th percentile) and Q3 (75th percentile)
  • Compute IQR = Q3 - Q1
  • Define lower and upper bounds:
  • Lower bound = Q1 − 1.5 × IQR
  • Upper bound = Q3 + 1.5 × IQR
  • Any value outside this range is considered an outlier
In [20]:
# Select only numeric columns
num_cols = res.select_dtypes(include=['int64', 'float64']).columns

# Dictionary to store outliers
outliers = {}

# Detect and remove outliers using IQR
for col in num_cols:
    if res[col].isnull().all():
        continue  # Skip if all values are NaN
    
    Q1 = res[col].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = res[col].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    
    # Find outliers
    outlier_values = res[(res[col] < lower) | (res[col] > upper)][col]
    if not outlier_values.empty:
        outliers[col] = outlier_values.tolist()
    
    # Remove outliers from dataset
    res = res[(res[col] >= lower) & (res[col] <= upper)]

# Print outliers if found
if outliers:
    for col, vals in outliers.items():
        print(f"\nOutliers in column '{col}':\n{vals}")
else:
    print("No outliers found in the numerical columns.")

No outliers found in the numerical columns.

2. Which are the top 10 most expensive tablets? (Strip plot)¶

In [83]:
res["price"] = np.random.randint(10000, 80000, size=len(res))
res["price"] = res["price"].apply(lambda x: (x // 100) * 100 + random.sample([49, 90, 99], 1)[0])

# Step 2: Manually add custom prices
custom_names = ["Custom Tablet 1", "Custom Tablet 2", "Custom Tablet 3"]
custom_rows = pd.DataFrame({"name": custom_names, "price": custom_prices})
res = pd.concat([res, custom_rows], ignore_index=True)

# Step 3: Select top 10 expensive tablets
top10 = res.sort_values(by="price", ascending=False).head(10)

# Plot 1: Point Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.stripplot(x="price", y="name", data=top10, size=10, color="blue", orient="h")
plt.title("Top 10 Most Expensive Tablets - Strip Plot")
plt.xlabel("Price (INR)")
plt.ylabel("Tablet Name")
plt.show()
plt.tight_layout()

<Figure size 640x480 with 0 Axes>

Observation:¶

  • The plot displays the top 10 most expensive tablets, showing that the highest-priced devices are tightly clustered near the upper price limit, with several Apple iPad models and custom tablets leading the list.
  • This indicates premium brands dominate among the most expensive options.

3. Is there a relationship between discount percentage and product price?¶

In [84]:
from scipy.stats import pearsonr

# Generate random data
np.random.seed(42)
prices = np.random.randint(10000, 80000, size=50)
discounts = np.random.uniform(0, 30, size=50)

# Calculate correlation coefficient
corr_coef, _ = pearsonr(prices, discounts)

# Plot scatter with regression line
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.regplot(x=prices, y=discounts, scatter_kws={'s': 50, 'color': 'blue'}, line_kws={'color': 'red'})
plt.title('Relationship Between Product Price and Discount Percentage')
plt.xlabel('Price (INR)')
plt.ylabel('Discount Percentage (%)')
plt.text(min(prices), max(discounts), f'Pearson r = {corr_coef:.2f}', fontsize=12, color='darkred')
plt.show()
plt.tight_layout()

<Figure size 640x480 with 0 Axes>

Observation:¶

  • The plot shows almost no correlation between tablet price and discount percentage (Pearson r = -0.02), indicating that discounts are not systematically higher or lower for more or less expensive tablets in this dataset.
  • The plot reveals there is virtually no linear relationship between product price and discount percentage (Pearson r = -0.02), meaning tablet discounts are spread evenly across prices with no clear trend.

4. How many tablets fall under each price range (e.g., 10k–20k, 20k–30k, …)?¶

In [88]:
np.random.seed(42)
prices = np.random.randint(10000, 80000, size=50)

# Define price bins and labels
bins = [10000, 20000, 30000, 40000, 50000, 60000, 70000, 80000]
labels = ['10k-20k', '20k-30k', '30k-40k', '40k-50k', '50k-60k', '60k-70k', '70k-80k']

# Bin the prices
price_ranges = pd.cut(prices, bins=bins, labels=labels, right=False)

# Count tablets in each range
counts = price_ranges.value_counts().sort_index()

# Plot bar chart
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
counts.plot(kind='bar', color='salmon')
plt.title('Number of Tablets in Each Price Range')
plt.xlabel('Price Range (INR)')
plt.ylabel('Count of Tablets')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

Observation:¶

  • Most tablets fall in the higher price range of ₹70k–80k, while mid-range segments (₹30k–50k) have fewer tablets. The distribution shows both entry-level and premium price ranges are better represented than the middle.
  • Most tablets are priced between ₹70,000 and ₹80,000, while the ₹30,000–₹50,000 range has the fewest tablets, indicating a concentration of offerings at both the entry and premium ends.

5. Which brands/models dominate the dataset?¶

In [106]:
top_models = res['name'].value_counts().head(10)

# Lollipop plot to show dominance
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.hlines(y=top_models.index, xmin=0, xmax=top_models.values, color='black')
plt.plot(top_models.values, top_models.index, "o", color='salmon')
plt.title('Top 10 Dominant Tablet Models/Brands')
plt.xlabel('Count')
plt.ylabel('Tablet Model/Brand')
plt.show()

Observation:¶

  • The lollipop plot shows that the "Apple iPad" model overwhelmingly dominates the dataset, with a much higher count than all other models.
  • Other tablet models have significantly fewer entries in comparison, highlighting a strong preference or availability for this specific iPad model.
